%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%
%                   Abstract
%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{abstract}
In this work, we propose an online causal structure learning framework that updates the prior belief as new streaming data is available and finally converges to the hidden underlying causal connectivity between variables. Directed Acyclic Graphs (DAGs) are the representative model to show causal interpretations among the entities and generally used to show how each variable is caused by its ancestors. In our framework, we assume causal data is emerged from different models such as structural equation models and structural autoregressive models and show that the proposed algorithm is effective. In the experiments, we show the algorithm is state-of-the-art in structure recovery and can find the connectivity in both batched and online cases. In addition, this framework is capable of adapt to changes in the underlying graph. Theoretical guarantees such as regret analysis is also under studies.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
DAG, graph signal processing, topology inference, structural equation model
\end{IEEEkeywords}


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%
%                   Section I
%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\section{Introduction}


\IEEEPARstart{C}{ausal} structure learning seeks to uncover the underlying cause-and-effect relationships among variables from observational data~\cite{causationspirtes}. Directed acyclic graphs (DAGs) provide a natural representation of causal models~\cite{peters2017elements}, Bayesian networks~\cite[Ch. 1.2.2]{Pearl_2009}, and the connections between variables in structrual equation models~\cite{loh2014high}. Recovering the topology of a DAG from data is a fundamental problem with applications spanning finance~\cite{finance}, biology~\cite{bio} and healthcare~\cite{lucas2004bayesian}.

A large body of work has been devoted to causal structure learning. Existing approaches can be broadly categorized into combinatorial optimization methods~\cite{chickering2002,ramsey2017}, order-based methods~\cite{topo,permutahedron,two2}, and continuous optimization frameworks~\cite{zheng2018dags,bello2022dagma,saboksayr2023colide}. While recent continuous optimization approaches have significantly improved scalability and accuracy, they are primarily designed for batch settings in which the entire dataset is available beforehand.

However, many modern applications generate data sequentially. Examples include financial markets, sensor networks, industrial monitoring systems, and biological processes, where observations arrive continuously over time~\cite{timeseries}. In such scenarios, retraining a causal model from scratch whenever new data becomes available is computationally inefficient and often impractical. Furthermore, the underlying causal structure may evolve, requiring learning algorithms that can adapt to changes while maintaining accurate estimates of the graph topology.

These challenges motivate the development of online causal structure learning methods. The objective is not only to recover the underlying DAG from streaming observations, but also to continuously refine prior estimates as new information becomes available. Compared with batch methods, online algorithms must balance statistical efficiency, computational complexity, and adaptability to nonstationary environments.

In this paper, we propose a novel online causal structure learning framework that incrementally updates the estimated causal graph as new data arrives. The proposed approach can operate under both structural equation models and structural vector autoregressive models, enabling the recovery of static as well as temporally dependent causal structures. The framework naturally accommodates batched and streaming observations and can adapt to changes in the underlying graph topology.

Extensive numerical experiments demonstrate that the proposed method achieves state-of-the-art performance in structure recovery while substantially reducing the computational burden associated with repeated batch retraining. In addition, we discuss ongoing efforts toward establishing theoretical guarantees, including convergence properties and regret bounds for the online learning process.

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section~II reviews the necessary background on causal graph models and continuous DAG learning. Section~III introduces the proposed online learning framework. Section~IV presents the corresponding optimization algorithm and implementation details. Section~V reports experimental results on synthetic and real datasets. Finally, Section~VI concludes the paper and discusses future research directions.\vspace{2pt}

\noindent \textbf{Notation.} Throughout this paper, scalars are denoted by lightface italic letters
(e.g., $x$), column vectors by boldface lowercase letters (e.g., $\bbx$),
and matrices by boldface uppercase letters (e.g., $\bbX$).
The $(i,j)$ entry of a matrix $\bbW$ is written $W_{ij}$ and its $j$th
column is $\bbw_j$. We use $\bbI_d \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d}$
for the identity matrix, $\bbzero$ for an all-zero matrix of context-dependent
size, $\odot$ for the Hadamard (entrywise) product, and $\|\cdot\|_F$,
$\|\cdot\|_1$, and $\|\cdot\|_2$ for the Frobenius, $\ell_1$, and spectral
norms, respectively. The sign function applied entrywise is denoted by
$\mathrm{sign}(\cdot)$, and $\mathrm{diag}(\bbv)$ produces a diagonal
matrix from a vector $\bbv$. Expected value is denoted by
$\mathbb{E}[\cdot]$. Given a time series $\{\bbx_t\}_{t=1}^{T}$, we collect
its observations in a matrix $\bbX = [\bbx_1, \ldots, \bbx_T]^\top
\in \mathbb{R}^{T \times d}$, where $(\cdot)^\top$ is the trace operator.


\section{Preliminaries and Related Work}
\label{sec:prelim}

\subsection{Notation}
Throughout this paper, scalars are denoted by lightface italic letters
(e.g., $x$), column vectors by boldface lowercase letters (e.g., $\bbx$),
and matrices by boldface uppercase letters (e.g., $\bbX$).
The $(i,j)$ entry of a matrix $\bbW$ is written $W_{ij}$ and its $j$th
column is $\bbw_j$. We use $\bbI_d \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d}$
for the identity matrix, $\bbzero$ for an all-zero matrix of context-dependent
size, $\odot$ for the Hadamard (entrywise) product, and $\|\cdot\|_F$,
$\|\cdot\|_1$, and $\|\cdot\|_2$ for the Frobenius, $\ell_1$, and spectral
norms, respectively. The sign function applied entrywise is denoted by
$\mathrm{sign}(\cdot)$, and $\mathrm{diag}(\bbv)$ produces a diagonal
matrix from a vector $\bbv$. Expected value is denoted by
$\mathbb{E}[\cdot]$. Given a time series $\{\bbx_t\}_{t=1}^{T}$, we collect
its observations in a matrix $\bbX = [\bbx_1, \ldots, \bbx_T]^\top
\in \mathbb{R}^{T \times d}$.


\subsection{Directed Acyclic Graphs and Linear Causal Models}
A directed acyclic graph (DAG) is a tuple $\mathcal{G} = (\mathcal{V},
\mathcal{E})$, where $\mathcal{V} = \{1, \ldots, d\}$ denotes the node set
and $\mathcal{E} \subseteq \mathcal{V} \times \mathcal{V}$ the directed edge
set, subject to the constraint that no directed cycles exist. Each node
$j \in \mathcal{V}$ is associated with a random variable $X_j$, and an edge
$(i, j) \in \mathcal{E}$ encodes that $X_i$ is a direct cause of $X_j$.
The graph is fully characterized by a weighted adjacency matrix
$\bbW \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d}$ whose entry $W_{ij}$ quantifies the
strength of the causal effect of $X_i$ on $X_j$, with $W_{ij} = 0$ iff
$(i,j) \notin \mathcal{E}$.

\textit{Structural Equation Model (SEM).} Given a DAG $\mathcal{G}$, the
linear SEM expresses each node as a noisy linear combination of its
parents:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:sem}
\bbX = \bbX\bbW + \bbZ,
\end{equation}
where each row of $\bbX \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times d}$ is an i.i.d. sample
of the joint distribution and $\bbZ \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times d}$ collects
the independent exogenous noises. In the equal-variance (EV) setting,
the noise satisfies $Z_{ij} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma^2)$; in the
non-equal variance (NV) setting, the columns admit node-specific
variances $\sigma_j^2$ for $j = 1, \ldots, d$, i.e.,
$Z_{ij} \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \sigma_j^2)$.

\textit{Structural Vector Autoregressive (SVAR) Model.} For
time-indexed data, the SVAR model extends the SEM with $p$ lagged terms
representing temporally delayed causal effects:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:svar}
\bbx_t = \bbW^\top \bbx_t + \sum_{k=1}^{p} \bbA_k^\top
\bbx_{t-k} + \bbz_t,
\end{equation}
where $\bbW \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d}$ is the contemporaneous DAG,
$\bbA_k \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d}$ encodes the temporal effects at
lag $k$, and $\bbz_t$ is the exogenous noise. Stacking the lagged
observations into a single matrix $\bbY \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times pd}$
where $\bbY = [\bbX_{-1}, \bbX_{-2}, \ldots, \bbX_{-p}]$ and
$\bbA \in \mathbb{R}^{pd \times d}$ vertically concatenates
$\{\bbA_k\}_{k=1}^{p}$, the SVAR model in matrix form reads
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:svar-matrix}
\bbX = \bbX\bbW + \bbY\bbA + \bbZ.
\end{equation}
Note that the acyclicity constraint applies only to $\bbW$, since
temporal ordering naturally rules out cycles in $\bbA$. When $p = 0$,
the model reduces to the static SEM in~\eqref{eq:sem}.

\textit{Reduced-form VAR.} Because $\mathcal{G}$ is acyclic, $\bbW$ can be
permuted to a strictly triangular matrix, so $\bbI_d - \bbW^\top$ is invertible
with $\det(\bbI_d - \bbW^\top) = 1$. Solving the contemporaneous part
of~\eqref{eq:svar} for $\bbx_t$ yields the \emph{reduced-form} vector
autoregression
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:reduced-var}
\bbx_t = \sum_{k=1}^{p} \bbC_k\,\bbx_{t-k} + \tilde{\bbz}_t,
\end{equation}
where $\bbC_k = (\bbI_d - \bbW^\top)^{-1}\bbA_k^\top$ are the reduced-form
(Granger) coefficient matrices and
$\tilde{\bbz}_t = (\bbI_d - \bbW^\top)^{-1}\bbz_t$ the mixed innovations. Stacking $p$ consecutive states into
$\bar{\bbx}_t = [\bbx_t^\top, \bbx_{t-1}^\top, \ldots, \bbx_{t-p+1}^\top]^\top
\in \mathbb{R}^{pd}$ casts~\eqref{eq:reduced-var} as the first-order recursion
$\bar{\bbx}_t = \bbF\,\bar{\bbx}_{t-1} + [\tilde{\bbz}_t^\top, \bbzero^\top]^\top$,
governed by the $pd \times pd$ companion matrix
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:companion}
\bbF =
\begin{bmatrix}
\bbC_1 & \bbC_2 & \cdots & \bbC_{p-1} & \bbC_p \\
\bbI_d & \bbzero & \cdots & \bbzero & \bbzero \\
\bbzero & \bbI_d & \cdots & \bbzero & \bbzero \\
\vdots & & \ddots & & \vdots \\
\bbzero & \bbzero & \cdots & \bbI_d & \bbzero
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{equation}

\textit{Stability and stationarity.} The SVAR process~\eqref{eq:svar} is
(weakly) stationary if and only if the companion matrix~\eqref{eq:companion} is
stable, i.e., its spectral radius lies strictly inside the unit circle,
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:stability}
\rho(\bbF) \;=\; \max_{i}\,\lvert \lambda_i(\bbF) \rvert \;<\; 1,
\end{equation}
or equivalently $\det\!\big(\bbI_d - \sum_{k=1}^{p}\bbC_k z^{k}\big) \neq 0$ for
all $z \in \mathbb{C}$ with $\lvert z \rvert \le 1$. Under~\eqref{eq:stability}
the process admits a unique stationary distribution with finite second moments,
so, writing $\bby_t = [\bbx_{t-1}^\top, \ldots, \bbx_{t-p}^\top]^\top$ for the
stacked lag vector, the population (cross-)covariances
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:stat-cov}
\bbSigma_{XX} = \mathbb{E}[\bbx_t \bbx_t^\top], \quad
\bbSigma_{XY} = \mathbb{E}[\bbx_t \bby_t^\top], \quad
\bbSigma_{YY} = \mathbb{E}[\bby_t \bby_t^\top]
\end{equation}
exist and are finite. These second-order statistics are precisely the
quantities tracked by the streaming estimators developed in this work; we
therefore take stability as a standing assumption throughout.

\subsection{Continuous Optimization for DAG Learning}
\label{sec:continuous-dag}
Recovering $\bbW$ from observational data is an NP-hard combinatorial
problem~\cite{chickering1996learning} when posed as a search over the
space of DAGs. NOTEARS~\cite{zheng2018dags} reformulated it as a continuous
optimization problem by introducing the differentiable acyclicity
characterization
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:notears-h}
h_{\mathrm{NT}}(\bbW) \;=\; \mathrm{tr}\!\left(e^{\bbW \odot \bbW}
\right) - d,
\end{equation}
which satisfies $h_{\mathrm{NT}}(\bbW) = 0$ if and only if $\bbW$ is
acyclic. The DAG learning problem can then be posed as
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:dag-prob}
\min_{\bbW \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d}}
\; \ell(\bbW; \bbX) + \lambda \|\bbW\|_1
\;\; \mathrm{s.t.} \;\; h(\bbW) = 0,
\end{equation}
where $\ell(\cdot)$ is a data-fitting term, $\lambda > 0$ controls
sparsity, and $h(\cdot)$ is a differentiable acyclicity penalty.

DAGMA~\cite{bello2022dagma} introduced a log-determinant alternative
that exhibits better gradient properties:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:dagma-h}
h_s(\bbW) \;=\; -\log\det\!\left(s\,\bbI_d - \bbW \odot \bbW
\right) + d \log s,
\end{equation}
defined for $s > 0$ on the domain where $s\,\bbI_d - \bbW \odot \bbW$
is an M-matrix. As $s$ is annealed toward smaller values, the penalty
$h_s(\bbW)$ tightens the acyclicity constraint, and an augmented
Lagrangian schedule is typically used to drive the solution toward
$h_s(\bbW) \approx 0$.

CoLiDE~\cite{saboksayr2023colide} further refined the score function by
treating the noise scale $\sigma$ as a free variable jointly optimized
with $\bbW$. In the EV setting, the CoLiDE score takes the form
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:colide-score}
S(\bbW, \sigma; \bbX)
\;=\; \frac{1}{2n\sigma}\,\|\bbX - \bbX\bbW\|_F^2
\;+\; \frac{d\sigma}{2} + \lambda \|\bbW\|_1,
\end{equation}
where $\sigma$ admits a closed-form update at each step. The NV
counterpart replaces the scalar $\sigma$ with a vector
$\sigma \in \mathbb{R}^d$ of per-node noise scales, similarly
admitting closed-form updates.

\subsection{Related Work}
\label{sec:related-work}
\textit{Combinatorial and constraint-based methods.} Classical DAG
learners include the score-based greedy equivalence search
(GES)~\cite{chickering2002}, its faster variant FGES~\cite{ramsey2017},
and the constraint-based PC~\cite{spirtes2000causation} and FCI
algorithms~\cite{spirtes1995fci}. These approaches operate over
combinatorial structures and scale poorly with dimension. Order-based
strategies~\cite{topo, permutahedron, two2} attempt to first recover a
topological order and then prune edges, achieving improved scalability
at the cost of order-search heuristics.

