\subsection{Continuous Optimization for DAG Learning}
\label{sec:continuous-dag}
Recovering $\bbW$ from observational data is an NP-hard combinatorial
problem~\cite{chickering1996learning} when posed as a search over the
space of DAGs. NOTEARS~\cite{zheng2018dags} reformulated it as a continuous
optimization problem by introducing the differentiable acyclicity
characterization
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:notears-h}
h_{\mathrm{NT}}(\bbW) \;=\; \mathrm{tr}\!\left(e^{\bbW \odot \bbW}
\right) - d,
\end{equation}
which satisfies $h_{\mathrm{NT}}(\bbW) = 0$ if and only if $\bbW$ is
acyclic. The DAG learning problem can then be posed as
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:dag-prob}
\min_{\bbW \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d}}
\; \ell(\bbW; \bbX) + \lambda \|\bbW\|_1
\;\; \mathrm{s.t.} \;\; h(\bbW) = 0,
\end{equation}
where $\ell(\cdot)$ is a data-fitting term, $\lambda > 0$ controls
sparsity, and $h(\cdot)$ is a differentiable acyclicity penalty.

DAGMA~\cite{bello2022dagma} introduced a log-determinant alternative
that exhibits better gradient properties:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:dagma-h}
h_s(\bbW) \;=\; -\log\det\!\left(s\,\bbI_d - \bbW \odot \bbW
\right) + d \log s,
\end{equation}
defined for $s > 0$ on the domain where $s\,\bbI_d - \bbW \odot \bbW$
is an M-matrix. As $s$ is annealed toward smaller values, the penalty
$h_s(\bbW)$ tightens the acyclicity constraint, and an augmented
Lagrangian schedule is typically used to drive the solution toward
$h_s(\bbW) \approx 0$.

CoLiDE~\cite{saboksayr2023colide} further refined the score function by
treating the noise scale $\sigma$ as a free variable jointly optimized
with $\bbW$. In the EV setting, the CoLiDE score takes the form
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:colide-score}
S(\bbW, \sigma; \bbX)
\;=\; \frac{1}{2n\sigma}\,\|\bbX - \bbX\bbW\|_F^2
\;+\; \frac{d\sigma}{2} + \lambda \|\bbW\|_1,
\end{equation}
where $\sigma$ admits a closed-form update at each step. The NV
