\subsection{Related Work}
\label{sec:related-work}
\textit{Combinatorial and constraint-based methods.} Classical DAG
learners include the score-based greedy equivalence search
(GES)~\cite{chickering2002}, its faster variant FGES~\cite{ramsey2017},
and the constraint-based PC~\cite{spirtes2000causation} and FCI
algorithms~\cite{spirtes1995fci}. These approaches operate over
combinatorial structures and scale poorly with dimension. Order-based
strategies~\cite{topo, permutahedron, two2} attempt to first recover a
topological order and then prune edges, achieving improved scalability
at the cost of order-search heuristics.

\textit{Continuous DAG learning.} Following
NOTEARS~\cite{zheng2018dags}, continuous formulations have proliferated:
GOLEM~\cite{ng2020golem} exchanges the hard acyclicity constraint for a
soft regularizer with explicit likelihood scoring; DAGMA improves
optimization geometry via the log-det penalty~\cite{bello2022dagma};
CoLiDE jointly estimates the noise scale and the DAG, yielding sharper
sparsity and better calibration to heteroscedastic
data~\cite{saboksayr2023colide}. Notably, all of these methods are
designed for the batch setting in which the entire dataset is available
a priori and revisited across optimization iterations.

\textit{Causal discovery for time series.} For SVAR-type data,
Dynotears~\cite{pamfil2020dynotears} extends NOTEARS by jointly
estimating the contemporaneous DAG and lag matrices under a shared
acyclicity penalty on $\bbW$. Constraint-based time-series methods such
as PCMCI and PCMCI$^+$~\cite{runge2019pcmci, runge2020pcmciplus} target
high-dimensional regimes by combining conditional independence tests
with a momentary conditional-independence step. VAR-LiNGAM
\cite{hyvarinen2010varlingam} exploits non-Gaussianity for
identifiability of both contemporaneous and lagged effects. As with the
static setting, these methods assume access to the full time series.

\textit{Online and streaming methods.} Online causal structure learning
remains comparatively under-explored. The few attempts in the
literature~\missref\ either revert to periodic full retraining of the
batch estimator or impose strong stationarity assumptions, with little
attention paid to per-sample computational cost or to the recovery of
both contemporaneous and lagged structures. In contrast, the framework
developed in this paper accommodates both SEM and SVAR data, processes
observations sequentially in mini-batches (including the true-online
$\mathrm{batch\_size} = 1$ regime), and adapts to time-varying DAGs.


\section{Problem Formulation}
\label{sec:problem}

This section formalizes the online DAG learning problem treated in the
remainder of the paper. We distinguish between the static (SEM) and
dynamic (SVAR) settings, and conclude with the operational desiderata
that the algorithms in Sections~\ref{sec:streaming-sem}
and~\ref{sec:streaming-svar} are designed to satisfy.

\subsection{Streaming Data Model}
\label{sec:streaming-data}
We consider a sequential observation protocol indexed by discrete time
$t = 1, 2, \ldots$. At each time $t$, the learner receives a batch
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:batch}
\bbX_t \;\in\; \mathbb{R}^{n_t \times d},
\end{equation}
where $n_t \geq 1$ denotes the number of $d$-dimensional samples observed
at time $t$. The case $n_t = 1$ corresponds to the \emph{true-online}
regime in which a single sample arrives per step, while $n_t > 1$
captures the \emph{mini-batch} streaming regime relevant for many
practical applications (e.g., periodic sensor readouts or chunked
financial observations). The cumulative dataset available at time $t$ is
denoted $\bbX^{(t)} = [\bbX_1^\top, \ldots, \bbX_t^\top]^\top$,
with running size $N_t = \sum_{\tau = 1}^{t} n_\tau$.

After processing the batch $\bbX_t$, the learner produces an updated
estimate $\widehat{\bbW}_t$ of the underlying DAG without revisiting the
full history $\bbX^{(t-1)}$. We make no assumption that $n_t$ is
constant across $t$, and we explicitly allow the case in which only a
sliding window of the most recent observations is retained in memory.

In the time-series (SVAR) setting, the streaming protocol is the same
except that observations arrive in temporal order; cross-batch lagged
dependencies are handled by maintaining a buffer of the last $p$
observations across batch boundaries, as described in
Section~\ref{sec:streaming-svar}.

\subsection{Online DAG Estimation under SEM}
\label{sec:problem-sem}
Suppose the data is generated by an unknown linear SEM with adjacency
matrix $\bbW^\star \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d}$ as in~\eqref{eq:sem},
where $\bbW^\star$ corresponds to a valid DAG. The streaming SEM
problem is to produce, at each time $t$, an estimate
$\widehat{\bbW}_t$ that minimizes the population risk
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:pop-risk-sem}
\mathcal{L}(\bbW, \sigma)
\;=\; \mathbb{E}\!\left[
  \tfrac{1}{2\sigma}\,\|\bbx - \bbW^\top \bbx\|_2^2
\right] + \tfrac{d \sigma}{2}
+ \lambda\,\|\bbW\|_1
\end{equation}
subject to the acyclicity constraint $h_s(\bbW) = 0$, while
\emph{only} accessing the sequentially-revealed batches
$\{\bbX_\tau\}_{\tau \leq t}$. The challenge is that the
expectation in~\eqref{eq:pop-risk-sem} is over the unknown data
distribution and must be approximated by running sample statistics that
are updated incrementally as $t$ grows.

\subsection{Online DAG Estimation under SVAR}
\label{sec:problem-svar}
Under the SVAR model~\eqref{eq:svar-matrix} with unknown contemporaneous
DAG $\bbW^\star$ and lag matrices $\{\bbA_k^\star\}_{k=1}^{p}$
stacked as $\bbA^\star \in \mathbb{R}^{pd \times d}$, the streaming
SVAR problem is to jointly produce estimates
$(\widehat{\bbW}_t, \widehat{\bbA}_t)$ that minimize the population
risk
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:pop-risk-svar}
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}(\bbW, \bbA, \sigma)
\;=\;& \mathbb{E}\!\left[ \tfrac{1}{2\sigma}\,
  \|\bbx_t - \bbW^\top \bbx_t - \bbA^\top \bby_t\|_2^2 \right]
\\
& + \tfrac{d\sigma}{2} + \lambda_{\bbW}\,\|\bbW\|_1
+ \lambda_{\bbA}\,\|\bbA\|_1,
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
where $\bby_t = [\bbx_{t-1}^\top, \ldots, \bbx_{t-p}^\top]^\top
\in \mathbb{R}^{pd}$ stacks the past $p$ observations, subject to
$h_s(\bbW) = 0$. As noted in Section~\ref{sec:prelim}, the acyclicity
constraint applies only to $\bbW$; the temporal-effect matrix $\bbA$
is regularized independently by an $\ell_1$ term with its own penalty
weight $\lambda_{\bbA}$.

\subsection{Time-Varying Causal Structure}
\label{sec:problem-evolving}
In nonstationary environments, the underlying DAG may itself evolve over
time. We model this by allowing the data-generating adjacency to be a
piecewise time-varying matrix $\bbW^\star_t$, capturing structural
changes such as regime shifts in financial markets, transient sensor
failures, or learning phases in biological systems. Specifically, we
consider trajectories
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:evolving-w}
\bbW^\star_t \;=\; \bbW^\star_{t-1} + \bbDelta_t,
\end{equation}
where $\bbDelta_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d}$ is a sparse perturbation
that may flip, remove, or add edges while preserving acyclicity. Under
this protocol the learner is no longer pursuing a single fixed minimizer
of~\eqref{eq:pop-risk-sem}; instead, the goal becomes \emph{tracking}, in
the sense that $\widehat{\bbW}_t$ should remain close to $\bbW^\star_t$
along the trajectory.

% \subsection{Operational Desiderata}
% \label{sec:design-goals}
% Beyond statistical consistency in the stationary case and tracking in the
% nonstationary case, an online DAG learning algorithm must satisfy several
% practical constraints. We highlight three that drive the design choices
% in Sections~\ref{sec:streaming-sem} and~\ref{sec:streaming-svar}:

% \begin{enumerate}
% \item \textbf{Bounded per-step cost.} The computational and memory cost
% of updating $\widehat{\bbW}_t$ given a new batch $\bbX_t$ must
% \emph{not} grow with $t$. This rules out approaches that re-run a
% full-batch optimizer on $\bbX^{(t)}$ at every step.

% \item \textbf{Consistency with the batch limit.} As $t \to \infty$ under
% stationary data, the streaming estimate should converge to the
% fixed point of the corresponding batch problem. This ensures that the
% online formulation does not pay a permanent statistical price for the
% restricted access pattern.

% \item \textbf{Adaptivity to structural change.} When the underlying DAG
% evolves as in~\eqref{eq:evolving-w}, the estimator should recover the
% new structure within a bounded delay after the change point, without
% requiring external change-detection signals or manual resets.
% \end{enumerate}

The algorithms developed in Sections~\ref{sec:streaming-sem}
and~\ref{sec:streaming-svar} achieve goals (1)--(2) via mini-batch
stochastic gradient descent on $(\bbW, \sigma)$ (and additionally
$\bbA$ in the SVAR case) coupled with closed-form online updates of
the relevant sample statistics. Goal~(3) is addressed by a sliding-window
variant, evaluated empirically in Section~\ref{sec:experiments}.


\section{Online DAG Learning under Streaming SEM}
\label{sec:streaming-sem}

This section develops the streaming counterpart of CoLiDE for the
static SEM~\eqref{eq:sem}. The algorithm processes mini-batches of
observations as they arrive, maintains a running sample covariance,
and produces an updated estimate $\widehat{\bbW}_t$ via stochastic
gradient descent on an augmented Lagrangian objective. Both the
equal-variance (EV) and non-equal variance (NV) noise regimes are
treated under a unified framework, differing only in the form of the
closed-form noise scale update.

\subsection{Augmented Lagrangian Formulation}
\label{sec:al-form}
We begin from the constrained problem
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:sem-constrained}
\min_{\bbW \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d},\, \sigma > 0}
\;\; S(\bbW, \sigma; \bbSigma) + \lambda\,\|\bbW\|_1
\;\;\; \mathrm{s.t.} \;\; h_s(\bbW) = 0,
\end{equation}
where $S(\bbW, \sigma; \bbSigma)$ is the CoLiDE
score~\eqref{eq:colide-score} expressed in terms of the data covariance
$\bbSigma = \mathbb{E}[\bbx\bbx^\top]$, namely
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:colide-score-cov}
S(\bbW, \sigma; \bbSigma)
\;=\; \frac{1}{2\sigma}
\mathrm{tr}\!\Big( (\bbI_d - \bbW)^\top \bbSigma\, (\bbI_d - \bbW) \Big)
+ \frac{d\sigma}{2}.
\end{equation}
Following DAGMA~\cite{bello2022dagma} and CoLiDE~\cite{saboksayr2023colide},
we relax the equality constraint via a sequence of weighted penalty
subproblems indexed by $i = 0, 1, \ldots, T-1$:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:al-subprob}
(\widehat{\bbW}^{(i)}, \widehat{\sigma}^{(i)})
\;\in\;
\arg\min_{\bbW, \sigma}
\; \mu_i\,\big[ S(\bbW, \sigma; \bbSigma)
+ \lambda\,\|\bbW\|_1 \big]
+ h_{s_i}(\bbW),
\end{equation}
where $\mu_i = \mu_0\,\rho^i$ with $\rho \in (0,1)$ is a geometrically
decaying score weight and $\{s_i\}$ is an annealed sequence approaching
the acyclicity-tight regime. The previous iterate
$(\widehat{\bbW}^{(i-1)}, \widehat{\sigma}^{(i-1)})$ warm-starts the
next subproblem, and the final iterate $\widehat{\bbW}^{(T-1)}$ is
returned as the estimate.

The key departure from the batch case is that $\bbSigma$
in~\eqref{eq:colide-score-cov} is unknown and must be replaced by a
sample-based proxy that is updated incrementally as data streams in.

\subsection{Streaming Sample Covariance}
\label{sec:online-cov}
Let $\bbSigma_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d}$ denote the running
estimate of $\bbSigma$ available at the start of SGD step $t$, with
$\bbSigma_0 = \bbzero$. Two complementary update rules are deployed
depending on the streaming regime:

\textit{Mini-batch regime ($n_t > 1$).} Given the centered batch
$\widetilde{\bbX}_t \in \mathbb{R}^{n_t \times d}$, the running
covariance is updated by the rank-one--style convex combination
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:cov-update-batch}
\bbSigma_t \;=\;
\frac{t - 1}{t}\,\bbSigma_{t-1}
+ \frac{1}{t}\,
\frac{1}{n_t}\,\widetilde{\bbX}_t^\top \widetilde{\bbX}_t,
\end{equation}
which is an unbiased and online-computable estimator of $\bbSigma$.

\textit{True-online regime ($n_t = 1$).} For single-sample updates,
\eqref{eq:cov-update-batch} is numerically unstable because each
$\widetilde{\bbX}_t$ has zero variance after centering. Instead, we
employ Welford's algorithm~\cite{welford1962} to jointly track the mean
$\bbmu_t$ and the running sum-of-squared-deviations
$\bbM_t \in \mathbb{R}^{d \times d}$:
\begin{align}
\label{eq:welford-mean}
\bbmu_t       &= \bbmu_{t-1} + \tfrac{1}{t}(\bbx_t - \bbmu_{t-1}), \\
\label{eq:welford-m2}
\bbM_t         &= \bbM_{t-1} + (\bbx_t - \bbmu_{t-1})(\bbx_t - \bbmu_t)^\top, \\
\label{eq:welford-cov}
\bbSigma_t    &= \bbM_t / t.
\end{align}
Both updates require $\mathcal{O}(d^2)$ time and memory per step,
independent of the cumulative sample count $N_t$, in line with
desideratum~(1) of Section~\ref{sec:design-goals}.

\subsection{Stochastic Gradient Updates on $\bbW$ and $\sigma$}
\label{sec:sgd-updates}
For each SGD step within the augmented-Lagrangian subproblem
\eqref{eq:al-subprob}, the score gradient with respect to $\bbW$
under the current running covariance $\bbSigma_t$ is given by
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:grad-w}
\nabla_{\bbW} S(\bbW, \sigma; \bbSigma_t)
\;=\; -\frac{1}{\sigma}\,\bbSigma_t\,(\bbI_d - \bbW).
\end{equation}
The corresponding update on the full augmented Lagrangian, including
the $\ell_1$ subgradient and the log-det acyclicity gradient
$\nabla_{\bbW} h_{s_i}(\bbW) = 2 \bbW \odot \bbM^{-\top}$ with
$\bbM = s_i \bbI_d - \bbW \odot \bbW$, becomes
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:full-grad-w}
\bbG_{\bbW}
\;=\; \mu_i\!\left( -\tfrac{1}{\sigma}\,\bbSigma_t\,(\bbI_d - \bbW)
+ \lambda\,\mathrm{sign}(\bbW) \right)
+ 2\,\bbW \odot \bbM^{-\top}.
\end{equation}
We apply an Adam~\cite{kingma2014adam} update to $\bbW$ using
$\bbG_{\bbW}$, yielding the new iterate $\bbW_{t+1}$. A
feasibility safeguard rolls back the update and halves the learning
rate if $\bbM$ loses positive-definiteness, ensuring that the log-det
penalty remains well-defined throughout the trajectory.

\textit{Equal-variance noise update.} For the EV setting, the optimal
$\sigma$ admits the closed-form
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:sigma-ev}
\widehat{\sigma}_t
\;=\;
\sqrt{
  \tfrac{1}{d}\,
  \mathrm{tr}\!\big( (\bbI_d - \bbW_{t+1})^\top
  \bbSigma_t (\bbI_d - \bbW_{t+1}) \big)
}.
\end{equation}

\textit{Non-equal variance noise update.} For the NV setting, where
$\sigma \in \mathbb{R}^d$ is a vector of per-node scales, the
closed-form update is applied component-wise:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:sigma-nv}
\widehat{\sigma}_{t,j}^{\,2}
\;=\;
\big[ (\bbI_d - \bbW_{t+1})^\top
\bbSigma_t\,(\bbI_d - \bbW_{t+1}) \big]_{jj},
\quad j = 1, \ldots, d.
\end{equation}
We emphasize that the NV update~\eqref{eq:sigma-nv} reuses the same
running covariance $\bbSigma_t$ as~\eqref{eq:sigma-ev}, differing
only by reading the diagonal instead of the trace. Heteroscedastic
residual-EMA alternatives, which decouple the $\sigma$ estimator from
the streaming covariance, were considered but discarded due to
inferior numerical stability under sustained streaming.

\subsection{Algorithm Summary}
\label{sec:colide-stream-algo}
Putting the pieces together, the streaming CoLiDE procedure is
summarized in Algorithm~\ref{alg:streaming-sem}. The outer loop
implements the augmented-Lagrangian schedule with annealed
$(\mu_i, s_i)$; the inner loop draws a fresh mini-batch (or
single sample, for $n_t = 1$), updates the running covariance, and
performs a single Adam step on $\bbW$ followed by the closed-form
$\sigma$ update.

\begin{algorithm}[t]
\caption{Streaming CoLiDE (SEM)}
\label{alg:streaming-sem}
\DontPrintSemicolon
\KwIn{stream $\{\bbX_t\}_{t \geq 1}$, sparsity $\lambda$,
schedules $\{\mu_i\}, \{s_i\}$ for $i = 0, \ldots, T-1$,
inner iterations $K_i$, learning rate $\eta$}
\KwOut{$\widehat{\bbW}$}
$\bbW_0 \gets \bbzero$, $\sigma_0 \gets 1$,
$\bbSigma_0 \gets \bbzero$\;
\For{$i = 0, 1, \ldots, T-1$}{
    reset Adam state for $\bbW$\;
    \For{$k = 1, \ldots, K_i$}{
        observe batch $\bbX_t$, center to $\widetilde{\bbX}_t$\;
        update $\bbSigma_t$ via~\eqref{eq:cov-update-batch}
        if $n_t > 1$, or~\eqref{eq:welford-mean}--\eqref{eq:welford-cov}
        if $n_t = 1$\;
        compute $\bbG_{\bbW}$ from~\eqref{eq:full-grad-w}\;
        $\bbW \gets \bbW - \eta \cdot \mathrm{Adam}(\bbG_{\bbW})$\;
        update $\sigma$ via~\eqref{eq:sigma-ev} (EV) or
        \eqref{eq:sigma-nv} (NV)\;
    }
}
\Return $\bbW$
\end{algorithm}

The per-step computational cost is dominated by the matrix inverse
$\bbM^{-1}$ in~\eqref{eq:full-grad-w}, which is
$\mathcal{O}(d^3)$, and by the covariance update, which is
$\mathcal{O}(n_t d^2)$. Memory is $\mathcal{O}(d^2)$ in both regimes,
independent of $N_t$. This complexity profile satisfies
desideratum~(1) of Section~\ref{sec:design-goals}, and the consistency
property of desideratum~(2) follows directly from the consistency of
$\bbSigma_t \to \bbSigma$ as $t \to \infty$, combined with the
fixed-point convergence of the augmented-Lagrangian schedule for the
batch CoLiDE problem~\cite{saboksayr2023colide}.


\section{Online DAG Learning under Streaming SVAR}
\label{sec:streaming-svar}

This section extends the streaming framework of
Section~\ref{sec:streaming-sem} to the SVAR
model~\eqref{eq:svar-matrix}. The defining new ingredient is that the
score now depends on \emph{three} second-order data statistics rather
than one, all of which must be tracked online from the streaming
observations. The contemporaneous DAG $\bbW$ and the lag matrix
$\bbA$ are updated jointly via stochastic gradient descent, while the
noise scale $\sigma$ continues to admit a closed-form update from the
running statistics. A cross-batch buffer of length $p$ resolves the
lagged dependencies that span batch boundaries.

\subsection{Augmented Lagrangian Formulation}
\label{sec:al-form-svar}
Recall from~\eqref{eq:svar-matrix} that the SVAR model couples
contemporaneous and lagged effects through
$\bbX = \bbX\bbW + \bbY\bbA + \bbZ$, where
$\bbY \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times pd}$ stacks the lagged observations
and $\bbA \in \mathbb{R}^{pd \times d}$ stacks the lag matrices
$\{\bbA_k\}_{k=1}^{p}$. Generalizing the score~\eqref{eq:colide-score}
to the SVAR setting, we define
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:dycolide-score}
S(\bbW, \bbA, \sigma; \bbX, \bbY)
\;=\;
\tfrac{1}{2n\sigma}\,\|\bbX - \bbX\bbW - \bbY\bbA\|_F^2
+ \tfrac{d\sigma}{2}.
\end{equation}
Letting $\bbSigma_{XX} = \tfrac{1}{n} \bbX^\top \bbX$,
$\bbSigma_{XY} = \tfrac{1}{n} \bbX^\top \bbY$, and
$\bbSigma_{YY} = \tfrac{1}{n} \bbY^\top \bbY$,
the score~\eqref{eq:dycolide-score} can be expressed entirely in terms
of these joint second-order statistics:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:dycolide-score-cov}
\begin{aligned}
S(\bbW, \bbA, \sigma)
\;=\;& \tfrac{1}{2\sigma}\,\Big[
  \mathrm{tr}\big( (\bbI_d - \bbW)^\top \bbSigma_{XX}\,
  (\bbI_d - \bbW) \big) \\
& - 2\,\mathrm{tr}\big( (\bbI_d - \bbW)^\top
  \bbSigma_{XY}\,\bbA \big)
+ \mathrm{tr}\big( \bbA^\top \bbSigma_{YY}\,\bbA \big)
\Big] \\
& + \tfrac{d \sigma}{2}.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
The constrained streaming SVAR problem is then
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:svar-constrained}
\begin{aligned}
\min_{\bbW, \bbA, \sigma > 0}
\;\;& S(\bbW, \bbA, \sigma)
+ \lambda_{\bbW}\,\|\bbW\|_1
+ \lambda_{\bbA}\,\|\bbA\|_1 \\
\mathrm{s.t.}\;& h_s(\bbW) = 0,
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
relaxed via the same augmented-Lagrangian schedule
$\{(\mu_i, s_i)\}_{i=0}^{T-1}$ used in~\eqref{eq:al-subprob}. Two
separate sparsity penalties $\lambda_{\bbW}$ and $\lambda_{\bbA}$
allow independent control of intra-slice and inter-slice density,
since the temporal effects in $\bbA$ are typically much weaker than
the contemporaneous effects in $\bbW$. As before, the acyclicity
penalty $h_{s}(\bbW)$ applies only to the contemporaneous component.

\subsection{Streaming Sample Covariances and Lag Buffering}
\label{sec:cov-svar}

At each SGD step $t$, the running estimates of the three statistics are
denoted by $\bbSigma_{XX, t}, \bbSigma_{XY, t},
\bbSigma_{YY, t}$, all initialized to zero. For the mini-batch
regime, the convex-combination update~\eqref{eq:cov-update-batch}
generalizes block-wise:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:svar-cov-update}
\bbSigma_{\bullet, t}
\;=\;
\tfrac{t-1}{t}\,\bbSigma_{\bullet, t-1}
+ \tfrac{1}{t}\,
\tfrac{1}{n_t}\,\widetilde{\bbX}_{\bullet, t}^\top
\widetilde{\bbY}_{\bullet, t}\,,
\quad \bullet \in \{XX, XY, YY\},
\end{equation}
where the suitable centered $\bbX$ or $\bbY$ batches are
substituted for each block. For the true-online regime ($n_t = 1$), the
joint Welford update~\eqref{eq:welford-mean}--\eqref{eq:welford-cov}
extends naturally to the concatenated vector
$[\bbx_t^\top, \bby_t^\top]^\top \in \mathbb{R}^{d + pd}$, after
which the three blocks of the joint $(d+pd) \times (d+pd)$ running
covariance are read off directly.

The construction of $\bby_t$, however, requires a small amount of
cross-batch state. Recall that
$\bby_t = [\bbx_{t-1}^\top, \ldots, \bbx_{t-p}^\top]^\top$
references observations from up to $p$ steps in the past. When the
batch boundary cuts across a lag-$p$ window, the first $p$ rows of the
new batch lack the lagged context needed to form valid
$(\bbx_t, \bby_t)$ row pairs. We resolve this by maintaining a
circular buffer $\mathcal{B}_t \in \mathbb{R}^{p \times d}$ of the last
$p$ observations across batch boundaries:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:buffer-update}
\mathcal{B}_t \;\leftarrow\; \mathrm{last\,}p(\,
\mathcal{B}_{t-1} \,\Vert\, \bbX_t\,)
\end{equation}
where $\Vert$ denotes vertical concatenation. Within batch $\bbX_t$,
the first $p$ rows are paired with lags drawn from $\mathcal{B}_{t-1}$,
and the buffer is then updated to retain the last $p$ rows of
$\bbX_t$ for the next step. This ensures that no row pair is dropped
at batch seams, at the cost of $\mathcal{O}(pd)$ additional memory.

\subsection{Joint Stochastic Updates on $\bbW$, $\bbA$, and $\sigma$}
\label{sec:sgd-svar}

Differentiating~\eqref{eq:dycolide-score-cov} with respect to $\bbW$
and $\bbA$ separately yields
\begin{align}
\label{eq:grad-w-svar}
\nabla_{\bbW} S
&= \tfrac{1}{\sigma}\big(
  \bbSigma_{XY, t}\,\bbA
- \bbSigma_{XX, t}\,(\bbI_d - \bbW)
\big), \\
\label{eq:grad-a-svar}
\nabla_{\bbA} S
&= \tfrac{1}{\sigma}\big(
  \bbSigma_{YY, t}\,\bbA
- \bbSigma_{XY, t}^{\,\top}(\bbI_d - \bbW)
\big),
\end{align}
both expressible directly in terms of the running statistics. Adding
the sparsity subgradients and the log-det acyclicity gradient (the
latter affecting only $\bbW$), the full augmented-Lagrangian
gradients within subproblem $i$ become
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:full-grad-w-svar}
\bbG_{\bbW} = \mu_i\!\left(
  \nabla_{\bbW} S
+ \lambda_{\bbW}\,\mathrm{sign}(\bbW)
\right) + 2\,\bbW \odot \bbM^{-\top},
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:full-grad-a-svar}
\bbG_{\bbA} = \mu_i\!\left(
  \nabla_{\bbA} S
+ \lambda_{\bbA}\,\mathrm{sign}(\bbA)
\right),
\end{equation}
where $\bbM = s_i \bbI_d - \bbW \odot \bbW$ as before. Two
independent Adam states are maintained for $\bbW$ and $\bbA$ within
each subproblem, and the feasibility safeguard for $\bbM$ continues
to apply.

Conditional on the updated $\bbW$ and $\bbA$, the closed-form
noise-scale update for the EV setting is obtained by reading the
trace of the residual covariance directly from the running statistics:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:sigma-ev-svar}
\begin{split}
\widehat{\sigma}_t^{\,2}
\;=\; \tfrac{1}{d}\,\Big[\;&
  \mathrm{tr}\big( (\bbI_d - \bbW)^\top \bbSigma_{XX, t}\,(\bbI_d - \bbW) \big) \\
&\quad - 2\,\mathrm{tr}\big( (\bbI_d - \bbW)^\top \bbSigma_{XY, t}\,\bbA \big)
+ \mathrm{tr}\big( \bbA^\top \bbSigma_{YY, t}\,\bbA \big) \Big].
\end{split}
\end{equation}
For the NV setting, \eqref{eq:sigma-ev-svar} is replaced by its
per-node diagonal analogue, in direct parallel
to~\eqref{eq:sigma-nv}; the only difference is that the residual
covariance comprises three terms instead of one.

\subsection{Algorithm Summary}
\label{sec:dycolide-stream-algo}

The streaming DyCoLiDE procedure is summarized in
Algorithm~\ref{alg:streaming-svar}. As in the SEM case, the outer loop
implements the augmented-Lagrangian schedule, while the inner loop
processes one mini-batch (or single observation) at a time, updates
the buffer and the three running covariances, and performs a single
Adam step on the joint parameter $(\bbW, \bbA)$ followed by the
closed-form $\sigma$ update.

\begin{algorithm}[t]
\caption{Streaming DyCoLiDE (SVAR)}
\label{alg:streaming-svar}
\DontPrintSemicolon
\KwIn{stream $\{\bbX_t\}_{t \geq 1}$, lag order $p$,
sparsity penalties $\lambda_{\bbW}, \lambda_{\bbA}$,
schedules $\{\mu_i\}, \{s_i\}$ for $i = 0, \ldots, T-1$,
inner iterations $K_i$, learning rate $\eta$}
\KwOut{$\widehat{\bbW}$, $\widehat{\bbA}$}
$\bbW_0 \gets \bbzero$,
$\bbA_0 \gets \bbzero$,
$\sigma_0 \gets 1$\;
$\bbSigma_{XX, 0}, \bbSigma_{XY, 0},
\bbSigma_{YY, 0} \gets \bbzero$;
buffer $\mathcal{B} \gets \emptyset$\;
\For{$i = 0, 1, \ldots, T-1$}{
    reset Adam states for $\bbW$ and $\bbA$\;
    \For{$k = 1, \ldots, K_i$}{
        observe batch $\bbX_t$\;
        form $(\bbX_t, \bbY_t)$ row pairs using
        $\mathcal{B}$ for the first $p$ rows\;
        update $\mathcal{B}$ via~\eqref{eq:buffer-update}\;
        center the batch and update
        $\bbSigma_{XX, t}, \bbSigma_{XY, t},
        \bbSigma_{YY, t}$ via~\eqref{eq:svar-cov-update}\;
        compute $\bbG_{\bbW}, \bbG_{\bbA}$
        via~\eqref{eq:full-grad-w-svar}--\eqref{eq:full-grad-a-svar}\;
        $\bbW \gets \bbW - \eta \cdot \mathrm{Adam}(\bbG_{\bbW})$\;
        $\bbA \gets \bbA - \eta \cdot \mathrm{Adam}(\bbG_{\bbA})$\;
        update $\sigma$ via~\eqref{eq:sigma-ev-svar} (EV) or
        its NV analogue\;
    }
}
\Return $\bbW, \bbA$
\end{algorithm}

The per-step cost is dominated by the $\mathcal{O}(d^3)$ matrix inverse
$\bbM^{-1}$ (unchanged from the SEM case) and by the running-covariance
updates, which incur $\mathcal{O}((d + pd)^2 n_t)$ work for the
$XY$ and $YY$ blocks. Memory remains $\mathcal{O}((d+pd)^2)
+ \mathcal{O}(pd)$ for the joint covariance and the buffer, independent
of the cumulative time index $t$. These bounds confirm that
Algorithm~\ref{alg:streaming-svar} satisfies the bounded-cost
desideratum~(1) of Section~\ref{sec:design-goals}, while the joint
consistency of the three running covariances under stationary data
ensures convergence to the batch DyCoLiDE-EV minimizer in the
$t \to \infty$ limit (desideratum~(2)). Empirical validation of both
properties, including the close agreement between
batch\_size $= 1$ (true online) and the full-batch reference, is
presented in Section~\ref{sec:experiments}.


\section{Adaptation to Time-Varying Causal Structure}
\label{sec:adaptation}

So far, the streaming framework of
Sections~\ref{sec:streaming-sem}--\ref{sec:streaming-svar} targets a
single, time-invariant ground-truth $\bbW^\star$ (and $\bbA^\star$
in the SVAR case). In nonstationary environments, the underlying DAG
itself evolves according to~\eqref{eq:evolving-w}, and the desideratum
shifts from convergence to \emph{tracking}: the estimator must follow
$\bbW^\star_t$ as it drifts or undergoes abrupt structural change.
This section describes a simple sliding-window variant of
Algorithms~\ref{alg:streaming-sem} and~\ref{alg:streaming-svar} that
satisfies desideratum~(3) of Section~\ref{sec:design-goals} without
requiring external change-detection signals.

\subsection{Sliding-Window Sample Statistics}
\label{sec:sliding-window}
The running covariance updates~\eqref{eq:cov-update-batch}
and~\eqref{eq:svar-cov-update} weight all past observations equally,
giving the most recent batch a vanishing influence as $t$ grows. This
behavior is desirable under stationarity but destructive when the
data-generating process changes, since the estimator becomes
arbitrarily slow to forget obsolete observations.

We instead retain a sliding buffer of the last $W$ observations,
$\mathcal{W}_t = \{\bbX_{t-W+1}, \ldots, \bbX_t\}$, and recompute
the sample covariance on this window:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:windowed-cov}
\bbSigma_t^{(W)}
\;=\;
\frac{1}{|\mathcal{W}_t|}
\sum_{\bbx \in \mathcal{W}_t}
(\bbx - \bar{\bbx}_{\mathcal{W}_t})
(\bbx - \bar{\bbx}_{\mathcal{W}_t})^\top,
\end{equation}
where $\bar{\bbx}_{\mathcal{W}_t}$ is the empirical mean over the
window. The window size $W$ controls the tracking--variance trade-off:
small $W$ adapts quickly to structural change but produces noisier
estimates; large $W$ smooths the estimates but introduces a lag of
order $\Theta(W)$ in following $\bbW^\star_t$. In the limit
$W \to \infty$ the sliding-window estimator coincides with the
all-history estimator of Sections~\ref{sec:streaming-sem}
and~\ref{sec:streaming-svar}.

\subsection{Tracking Behavior under Structural Change}
\label{sec:tracking}
Consider a piecewise-stationary trajectory in which
$\bbW^\star_t = \bbW_1^\star$ for $t < t^\star$ and
$\bbW^\star_t = \bbW_2^\star$ for $t \geq t^\star$, with
$\bbDelta = \bbW_2^\star - \bbW_1^\star$ supported on a small
edge set. The sliding-window streaming estimator exhibits three
distinct regimes:
\begin{enumerate}
\item \emph{Pre-change ($t < t^\star$).} The window
$\mathcal{W}_t$ contains only samples from the $\bbW_1^\star$
regime; the estimator converges to $\bbW_1^\star$ at the rate
dictated by the inner CoLiDE/DyCoLiDE optimization.

\item \emph{Transition ($t^\star \leq t < t^\star + W$).} The window
contains a mixture of pre- and post-change samples whose proportions
shift linearly. The estimator's score function interpolates between
the two regimes, producing intermediate estimates whose support
straddles $\bbW_1^\star$ and $\bbW_2^\star$.

\item \emph{Post-adaptation ($t \geq t^\star + W$).} The window
contains only samples from the $\bbW_2^\star$ regime; the
estimator converges to $\bbW_2^\star$ at the same rate as in the
pre-change phase.
\end{enumerate}
The adaptation delay is therefore approximately $W$ batches, with the
window size acting as a direct knob on the bias--variance--latency
trade-off. Empirically (Section~\ref{sec:experiments}) we observe
sharper transitions than this idealized analysis predicts, since the
augmented-Lagrangian schedule causes the inner optimizer to commit to
the dominant regime in the window once a majority of samples agrees.

\subsection{Algorithm and Cost}
\label{sec:adaptation-algo}
The sliding-window variant differs from
Algorithms~\ref{alg:streaming-sem} and~\ref{alg:streaming-svar} in only
two respects: (i) the running-covariance update is replaced by the
windowed estimator~\eqref{eq:windowed-cov}, and (ii) the augmented
Lagrangian is rerun on the current window at each new batch arrival,
warm-started from the previous estimate $\widehat{\bbW}_{t-1}$.
Memory grows from $\mathcal{O}(d^2)$ to $\mathcal{O}(W d)$ to store the
sliding buffer, which remains independent of the cumulative time index
$t$. Per-batch computation is dominated by the inner CoLiDE/DyCoLiDE
solve on the window, which inherits the $\mathcal{O}(d^3)$ matrix-inverse
cost of the static algorithms.

In practice, the warm-start from $\widehat{\bbW}_{t-1}$ allows the
inner solver to converge in far fewer iterations than a cold start
would require, particularly during stationary phases when consecutive
windows differ by a single batch. As the window slides forward and the
data shifts, the warm-start gracefully degrades into a fresh
optimization, providing a natural form of computational efficiency
without the need for an explicit change-detection module.


\section{Numerical Experiments}
\label{sec:experiments}

This section presents an empirical evaluation of the proposed streaming
framework. We address four questions: (i) Does the mini-batch streaming
variant of CoLiDE recover the same DAG as the full-batch reference
across graph sizes and densities? (ii) Does the SVAR extension
exhibit the same behavior on time-series data? (iii) How sensitive
are the resulting estimates to the sparsity hyperparameters
$(\lambda_{\bbW}, \lambda_{\bbA})$? (iv) Can the sliding-window
variant track a time-varying DAG through abrupt structural change?

\subsection{Experimental Setup}
\label{sec:exp-setup}

\textit{Synthetic data.} For the SEM experiments, we generate
Erd\H{o}s--R\'enyi DAGs $\bbW^\star$ with $d \in \{20, 40, 60, 80,
100\}$ nodes and average degree $\bar{k} \in \{2, 3, 4\}$ (referred to
as ER2, ER3, and ER4 respectively). Edge weights are drawn uniformly
from $[-2.0, -0.5] \cup [0.5, 2.0]$, and $n = 1000$ samples are drawn
from the linear SEM~\eqref{eq:sem} with either equal-variance (EV)
unit-variance Gaussian noise or heteroscedastic (NV) noise with
per-node variances sampled from $[0.5, 10.0]$.

For the SVAR experiments, we use $d \in \{10, 20, 30, 40, 50\}$ nodes,
ER densities $\bar{k} \in \{2, 3, 4\}$ for both the contemporaneous and
lag-$1$ matrices, $T_\mathrm{steps} = 1000$ time points, and
temporal-effect strength $0.5$, calibrated to satisfy companion-matrix
stability. Tuned hyperparameters $\lambda_{\bbW} = 0.01$,
$\lambda_{\bbA} = 0.015$ are used unless otherwise noted. All
estimates are binarized at the threshold $0.10$ for SHD computation.

\textit{Baselines.} We compare four estimators throughout: the
full-batch static reference (\textsc{Static}), and three streaming
variants distinguished by their batch size:
$\mathrm{batch\_size} \in \{100, 50, 1\}$, where
$\mathrm{batch\_size} = 1$ corresponds to the true-online Welford
regime. All four methods share an identical augmented-Lagrangian
schedule ($T = 4$ outer iterations, $K_\mathrm{warm} = 20{,}000$ inner
steps for the first three subproblems and $K_\mathrm{final} = 70{,}000$
for the last) and the same Adam learning rate $\eta = 3 \times 10^{-4}$.

\textit{Metrics.} We report two complementary recovery metrics. The
\emph{structural Hamming distance} (SHD) counts the number of edge
flips (missing + extra) between the thresholded estimate and the
ground-truth binary adjacency. The \emph{normalized mean squared
error} (NMSE) on the weighted estimates is defined as
$\mathrm{NMSE}(\widehat{\bbW}, \bbW^\star) =
\|\widehat{\bbW} - \bbW^\star\|_F^2 /
\|\bbW^\star\|_F^2$. All reported numbers are mean $\pm$ standard
deviation over five independent seeds, drawn from
$\{42, 43, 44, 45, 46\}$. The same data realization is fed to all four
methods within each $(\bar{k}, d, \mathrm{seed})$ cell.

\subsection{Streaming SEM Recovery}
\label{sec:exp-sem}
Tables~\ref{tab:sem-ev-shd}--\ref{tab:sem-nv-nmse} summarize SHD and
NMSE for both noise regimes across the $d \times \bar{k} \times
\text{method}$ grid; the corresponding bar-plot view with $25$--$75\%$
interquartile-range error bars is shown in Figure~\ref{fig:sem-scaling}
(\textit{omitted for brevity}). The headline observation is that the
streaming variants and the full-batch reference produce statistically
indistinguishable estimates at every cell. As a representative example
from Table~\ref{tab:sem-ev-shd}, at $d = 100$, ER4, EV noise, the mean
SHD values are $38.2 \pm 28.3$ (\textsc{Static}), $41.8 \pm 27.8$
($\mathrm{bs} = 100$), $41.8 \pm 27.8$ ($\mathrm{bs} = 50$), and
$38.0 \pm 27.3$ ($\mathrm{bs} = 1$), with all four methods overlapping
within one standard deviation.

The same agreement persists under heteroscedastic noise, summarized in
Table~\ref{tab:sem-nv-shd}. For the NV setting at $d = 100$, ER4, the
mean SHD values are $108.6 \pm 14.3$, $111.4 \pm 11.6$, $113.4 \pm 11.1$,
and $113.4 \pm 19.9$ across the four methods respectively---again
overlapping within margin. NV recovery is uniformly more difficult
than EV at the same configuration, an effect visible by comparing
Tables~\ref{tab:sem-ev-shd} and~\ref{tab:sem-nv-shd} cell-by-cell;
the per-node $\bbsigma$ reweighting in~\eqref{eq:sigma-nv} only
partially compensates for the increased estimation difficulty. The
weighted-recovery story (NMSE) in
Tables~\ref{tab:sem-ev-nmse} and~\ref{tab:sem-nv-nmse} mirrors the
SHD pattern, confirming that the binary and continuous metrics agree
on which cells are easy versus difficult.

\textit{Effect of sparsity tuning.} The default $\lambda = 0.05$ used
in the experiments above can be improved at small graph sizes via
per-density tuning. We swept
$\lambda \in \{0.005, 0.01, 0.02, 0.03, 0.05, 0.08, 0.12, 0.2\}$ at
$d = 20$ across all three ER levels and found best values of
$0.02$ (ER2), $0.02$ (ER3), and $0.03$ (ER4), corresponding to
reductions in mean SHD of $0\%$, $21\%$, and $32\%$ relative to the
$\lambda = 0.05$ baseline. The d=20 column in
Tables~\ref{tab:sem-ev-shd} and~\ref{tab:sem-ev-nmse} uses these tuned
values; the same exercise at $d = 40$ yields best values of $0.03$
(ER2), $0.02$ (ER3), and $0.02$ (ER4), and the corresponding column
in those tables likewise reflects the tuned configuration.
Crucially, the SHD-optimal $\lambda$ values remain consistent across
all four methods, confirming that the streaming variants share the
same loss landscape as the full-batch reference.

\input{tables.tex}

\subsection{Streaming SVAR Recovery}
\label{sec:exp-svar}
For SVAR data, we evaluate the mini-batch
DyCoLiDE-EV-batch variant introduced in
Section~\ref{sec:streaming-svar} against the full-batch
DyCoLiDE-EV~\eqref{eq:dycolide-score} reference, and separately the
NV variant against the full-batch DyCoLiDE-NV. A representative
configuration is reported in Table~\ref{tab:svar-d20-er2} for
$d = 20$, ER2. Under EV noise, all four methods agree to within
$0.6$ SHD on both the contemporaneous DAG $\bbW$ and the temporal
$\bbA$. Under NV noise, the full-batch \textsc{Static}-NV fails to
converge at any $\lambda$ in the swept range; the three mini-batch
variants share a single fixed point (W~SHD $\approx 13$, A~SHD
$\approx 20$), supporting the consistency claim of
Section~\ref{sec:streaming-svar} also for the heteroscedastic case.

Across the broader $d \times \bar{k} \times \text{method}$ grid, all
four EV methods recover nearly identical estimates of both $\bbW$ and
$\bbA$. For instance, at $d = 30$, ER2, the mean
W-side SHD values are $13.4 \pm 10.5$, $11.2 \pm 9.2$,
$7.4 \pm 6.0$, and $13.4 \pm 10.5$ for \textsc{Static},
$\mathrm{bs} = 100$, $\mathrm{bs} = 50$, and $\mathrm{bs} = 1$
respectively; the A-side SHD values agree to within $1.2$ edges across
all four methods.

The W side is recovered substantially more accurately than the A side
at all configurations: average W SHD remains in the single digits
through $d = 30$ across all ER levels, while A SHD scales roughly
linearly with $d$ and $\bar{k}$. This asymmetry reflects two
structural facts. First, the contemporaneous DAG has only $d^2$ free
parameters, whereas $\bbA$ has $p d^2$ free parameters and lacks the
acyclicity constraint that sharpens identification of $\bbW$.
Second, the SVAR stability requirement places an upper bound on
$\|\bbA\|$ that depends on the spectral radius of the companion
matrix, causing many true A entries to fall below the binarization
threshold even when correctly identified by sign. A threshold sweep
(omitted for brevity) confirms that this is a binary-decision artifact
rather than a regularization artifact.

\subsection{Adaptation to Time-Varying Causal Structure}
\label{sec:exp-evolving}

To assess the tracking behavior described in
Section~\ref{sec:adaptation}, we run the sliding-window streaming
estimator on a piecewise-stationary stream for both the SEM and the
SVAR data-generating models. In each case we use $d = 20$ nodes, ER2
density, total stream length $T = 2000$, and change point at
$t^\star = T/2$. The post-change graph $\bbW_2^\star$ (and $\bbA_2$
for SVAR) retains $50\%$ of the edges of $\bbW_1^\star$ ($\bbA_1$) and
replaces the remainder with fresh edges drawn from the same
distribution. Data arrives in mini-batches of $100$ samples and the
estimator maintains a sliding window of $W = 500$ samples. At each
batch arrival the model is refit on the window, warm-started from the
previous batch's estimate, and the $W$- and $A$-side structural Hamming
distances are evaluated against the \emph{active} ground truth
($\bbW_1^\star$ before $t^\star$, $\bbW_2^\star$ afterwards). All
metrics are reported as median values across three independent data
realizations; shaded bands in Figure~\ref{fig:evolving-streaming}
indicate the $25$--$75\%$ inter-quantile range.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{figures/streaming_evolving_sem_svar.png}
\caption{Streaming recovery under a mid-stream DAG change for both SEM
(top row, $\bbW$-side SHD and TPR) and SVAR (bottom row, $\bbW$- and
$\bbA$-side SHD), at $d=20$, ER2, $\mathrm{batch}=100$, $W=500$,
$t^\star = 1000$. Each curve plots the per-batch median (line) and
$25$--$75\%$ inter-quantile range (shaded) across three data
realizations. The blue segment scores the estimate against the
pre-change ground truth, the red segment against the post-change
ground truth; the dashed green line marks the change point. The drop
at $t = t^\star + W = 1500$ corresponds to the moment the sliding
window has fully refilled with post-change samples.}
\label{fig:evolving-streaming}
\end{figure}

The figure shows the predicted three-phase shape in all four panels:
(i)~a low-SHD plateau through the pre-change regime, (ii)~a transient
spike of $\Theta(W)$ samples during which the window contains a
mixture of pre- and post-change data, and (iii)~a return to the same
low-SHD plateau against the new ground truth once the window is fully
post-change at $t = t^\star + W$.

\textit{SEM.} The median $\bbW$-SHD against $\bbW_1^\star$ converges
to $9$ at the end of the pre-change regime
($\mathrm{TPR}(\bbW_1) = 0.97$), spikes to a peak of $72$ during
window mixing, and drops to
$\mathbf{0}$ ($\mathrm{TPR}(\bbW_2) = 1.00$) at $t = 1500$, where it
remains for the rest of the stream. The transition occupies exactly
$\Theta(W / \mathrm{batch\_size}) = 5$ batches, matching the analysis
of Section~\ref{sec:tracking}.

\textit{SVAR.} The contemporaneous side is recovered near-exactly in
both regimes: the median $\bbW$-SHD settles to $5$ pre-change and
$\mathbf{3}$ post-change ($\mathrm{TPR}(\bbW_2)\!\approx\!1$). The
$\bbA$-side reaches a pre-change floor of $23$ and a post-change
floor of $26$; the small residual is attributable to true $\bbA$
entries whose magnitudes lie close to the binarization threshold
after the stability-decay loop required by the SVAR companion
constraint, not to a failure of adaptation---the curve is flat from
$t = 1500$ through $t = T$, confirming that the model has converged
to $\bbA_2$. Pre- and post-change SHD floors match to within
single-edge precision on both sides, evidence that the streaming
estimator tracks the new structure with the same quality it achieved
on the old one.

\subsection{Summary of Empirical Findings}
\label{sec:exp-summary}
The experiments confirm the three operational desiderata of
Section~\ref{sec:design-goals}. The streaming estimators of
Algorithms~\ref{alg:streaming-sem} and~\ref{alg:streaming-svar} are
statistically equivalent to their full-batch counterparts under both
the SEM and SVAR data-generating models, across a wide range of graph
sizes and densities, and the agreement is robust to the choice of
batch size, including the true-online $\mathrm{batch\_size} = 1$
regime. The sliding-window variant achieves zero-SHD recovery after a
predictable, window-bounded adaptation delay following abrupt
structural change. Together, these results establish the streaming
framework as a drop-in replacement for batch DAG learning whenever
sequential data access or graph nonstationarity precludes the latter.


\section{Conclusions and Future Work}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We presented an online causal structure learning framework that learns
linear DAGs from streaming observational data under both static
(SEM) and dynamic (SVAR) generative models. The framework augments
the CoLiDE family with running estimators of the relevant second-order
statistics---a single covariance $\bbSigma_t$ for SEM and the joint
block $(\bbSigma_{XX}, \bbSigma_{XY},
\bbSigma_{YY})$ for SVAR---and a mini-batch SGD inner loop
that updates the DAG estimate at $\mathcal{O}(d^2)$ memory and
$\mathcal{O}(d^3)$ time per step, independent of the cumulative sample
count. The closed-form noise-scale updates of CoLiDE remain in force
in both equal-variance and heteroscedastic regimes, with the
heteroscedastic case handled via the diagonal of the same residual
covariance used in the EV closed form. A sliding-window variant
extends the same machinery to nonstationary settings in which the
underlying DAG evolves over time.

Empirically, the streaming variants are statistically equivalent to
the full-batch CoLiDE/DyCoLiDE reference across a wide range of node
counts and edge densities, including the true-online
$\mathrm{batch\_size} = 1$ regime backed by Welford's algorithm.
Under abrupt structural change, the sliding-window estimator recovers
the new DAG exactly within a delay matching the
$\Theta(W/\mathrm{batch\_size})$ analysis. These findings support our
central claim: streaming and batch DAG learning need not differ in
recovery quality at convergence---only in per-step cost and
adaptivity to drift.

Several directions remain open. \emph{Theoretical analysis.} The
regret behavior of the streaming estimator under stationary and
piecewise-stationary trajectories of $\bbW^\star_t$ is not yet
characterized; an $\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{T})$ static regret bound and a
matching dynamic regret bound under a path-length budget on
$\{\bbW^\star_t\}$ would mirror standard results in online convex
optimization and lend formal grounding to the empirical tracking
behavior observed in Section~\ref{sec:exp-evolving}.
\emph{Warm-starting and per-batch reuse.} The current sliding-window
variant resolves each augmented-Lagrangian subproblem to convergence
at every batch arrival. A truly incremental scheme would
warm-start not only the iterate $\bbW_t$ but also the Adam moment
estimates and the augmented-Lagrangian schedule index, plausibly
reducing per-batch cost by an order of magnitude. \emph{Threshold and
hyperparameter adaptation.} The SVAR experiments revealed a binary
decision artifact in which a static threshold mis-classifies weak
true edges as missing; a data-driven threshold (e.g., chosen by
post-hoc edge-weight clustering) and an online schedule for the
sparsity penalties $(\lambda_{\bbW}, \lambda_{\bbA})$ would
address this without inflating false positives.
\emph{Beyond linear and Gaussian.} The framework presented here
inherits the linear-Gaussian assumptions of CoLiDE; extensions to
non-Gaussian noise via LiNGAM-style identifiability arguments, and to
nonlinear SEMs via neural-network parameterizations of the structural
equations, would broaden applicability to a wider class of real-world
processes. \emph{Real-data evaluation.} All experiments reported here
use synthetic data with known ground truth. Application of the
streaming framework to genuinely sequential real-world datasets---in
financial-market regime detection, neural-population dynamics, or
industrial sensor monitoring---is the natural next step in
establishing its practical utility.



